<font color="#FF0000">A LONG WINDING ROAD AT 90 MPH</font><br>
<tt>Sat Aug 16 23:27:42 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Well, I go away on detached duty to a veterans' convention and you guys go and have the fun of a 90+ post-a-thon without me.  This thread has taken more twists and turns in a short stretch than your avaerage West Virginia highway.  Sorry I missed the roll call, Chet.<br><br>
Something weird is happening here.  I tried to post last night, and ran into an &quot;inactive thread message&quot;.  Lost the post after an hour's thought and work.  Now I find that some posts are missing, particularly all those from a &quot;lima zulu&quot;.  Yo, Marc, Site Administrator, WHAT GIVES?<br><br>
As I noted on another thread, it appears to be ANYONE vs DOC SPATZ.  I don't see eye to eye politically with Doc, but his opponents are going out of the way to pile on in some instances in ways that I find embarassing as a veteran.  The enemy we killed or were responsible for getting killed consisted of Communists at the top, but the infantry that bled and died in much greater numbers than our side consisted of drafted peasants that fought for their country in the same spirit Cook and the rest fought for ours.  Marxist doctrine for them was something they had shoved down their throats by higher authority.  I doubt if most knew Engels from Trotsky.  Cook, if you must believe that all the troops you fought were &quot;Commie Gooks&quot; in order to feel that you fought honorably, I pity you, because you're living an illusion.  That's like saying all German WWII soldiers wre Nazis, all Italian WWII troops were Fascists and all Confederates were pro-slavery racists.  Our involvement in Vietnam ended 24-25 years ago. To say it helped end the cold war in our favor after the passage of so much time is quite debatable.  For myself, as I've gone into detail elsewhere; I believe the Vietnam War was a mistake on balance looking at ALL its fruit, but that does NOT mean I've ever been ashamed of my service, despite being personally called a &quot;baby killer&quot;.  At the time I acted to apply my principles the best way I knew how, and that was to obey my orders to Vietnam, and do my best to do my duty.  In an imperfect, complicated world, perfect knowledge leading to absolute moral certainty of the rightness are not found much above the level of daily personal decisions.  It's easy to say, &quot;Cheating on a test, Stealing $100 or Burning a cross on someone's lawn&quot; is wrong, but weighing the multiple pros and cons, some unknown or only partially known, is a difficult matter of judgement.  History shows that many with the best intentions get the answer wrong whether they decide Yes or No.<br><br>
PS. On a lighter note for Chet, DocDel, Doc Spatz &amp; Tom:  In high school I was the &quot;good kid&quot; with glasses, good grades, poor athletic ability, corduroy pants, no date much less a girlfriend (only 3 dates in HS, 6 in college - got stood up for UWM homecoming),  paper route, accordian, French Horn and no car.  Liked to dance to Rock, but listened to classical &amp; easy listening music at home.  Was not just a Square but a CUBE.
<p><code>-- gerald_ney@icpphil.navy.mil  (Gerald Ney, &quot;professor&quot;, 7/68-7/69) </code><p>


